Elon Musk is forced to leave the post of Chairman of the Board of Directors of Tesla
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and Tesla founder Elon Musk have settled their dispute over the fraud case.
This is reported by CNBC News.
According to the TV channel, as part of the agreements, Musk will have to leave the post of the head of the board of directors of Tesla.
At the same time, the commission allowed Musk to retain the post of Tesla's head.
As noted, the founder of Tesla will also have to pay an administrative fine of $ 20 million.
The same amount will be charged to Tesla.
The money will be distributed among the affected investors.
In addition, the company must appoint two independent directors.
Elon Musk is an American entrepreneur, included in the list of the 50 richest people on the planet according to Forbes magazine.
He is the head of the SpaceX space corporation, neurotech company Neuralink and the developer of Tesla electric cars, as well as the co-founder of Paypal.
The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission earlier sued Tesla CEO Elon Musk over his tweet about a possible buyout of the company.
Last month, Musk announced plans to make Tesla a private company and buy back all shares on the stock exchange at a fixed price of $420.
The price of the share of $ 420 was established allegedly "because of the importance of this number in the culture of marijuana," Bloomberg reported earlier, citing the co-director of the security department of the Commission Stephen Peikin.
At the same time, Elon Musk subsequently abandoned his plans to buy shares.
Commenting on the lawsuit filed against him by the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, the businessman said that he considers the accusations of fraud unfounded, and added that he is very disappointed and saddened by these claims.
“Honesty is the most important value in my life, and the facts will prove that I didn’t break it in any way,” he told CNBC.
In August, a group of Tesla shareholders filed a class action lawsuit against Musk, complaining of financial losses.
The plaintiffs claimed that the posts of the businessman brought them losses.
In particular, one of the shareholders said that the businessman’s tweets were misleading, which caused Tesla stock sellers to be forced to buy securities at artificially inflated prices to cover their positions.
Also, other plaintiffs noted that the careless statements of Elon Musk led to sharp fluctuations in the course.
In September, Elon Musk accused the head of the research company Citron Research of exchange fraud.
Meanwhile, if Musk could not settle his dispute with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, he would face suspension from the company and even prison.
This, in particular, told CNBC channel former chairman of the Commission Harvey Pitt.
Musk is “a good guy who doesn’t know how to run a car company.”
