In Indonesia, after the earthquake, more than 100 prisoners escaped from prison
More than 100 prisoners have escaped from a prison in Indonesia’s Central Sulawesi province.
The escape was possible after two powerful earthquakes on the island of magnitude 7.2 and 7.4.
According to the newspaper The Jakarta Post, the incident occurred on September 28, when detainees in the prison of the city of Palu demanded their release due to tremors.
More than 340 prisoners staged a riot and set fire to the institution.
Police officers who arrived on the scene partially took control of the situation, but more than 100 people escaped from prison.
The building itself has been severely damaged and guards are finding it difficult to hold prisoners.
The number of victims of the earthquake and tsunami that occurred on the island of Sulawesi, increased to 832 people.
Transport links, electricity and communications with certain areas of the island are still not established.
"Golden Pearl" for "ultimate realism"
For the third time in history, the San Sebastian International Film Festival recognized the Spanish film of the year as the best film of the year.
The main award - "Golden sink" - was awarded to the drama "Between two seas" directed by Isaki Laquesta.
This film with almost documentary realism tells the difficult story of the lives of two brothers in the Spanish seaside province of Cádiz - Lacuesta presented the continuation of his 2006 film "The Legend of Time".
