Kosachev: At the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly, the theme of Russia in a negative way was practically absent
The head of the Federation Council Committee on International Affairs Konstantin Kosachev considers the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly successful for Russia and does not exclude that it will be able to become a turning point in the perception of the Russian Federation as an integral participant in solving global world problems.
“The uniqueness of the current 73rd session, in my opinion, is that the rhetoric to which we have almost become accustomed in recent years in relation to Russia, was now an order of magnitude more muted,” the senator said in an interview published Sunday by Rossiyskaya Gazeta.
He explained that in previous years, the Russian Federation was sometimes “designated as one of the three main threats to humanity, along with Ebola, along with climate change or terrorism, Russia was in this row, at least in the statement of a group of Western countries, which in this regard spoke quite unanimously.”
At the 73rd session, Kosachev stressed, “the theme of Russia in a negative way was almost absent.”
“If you carefully analyze the speech of the President of the United States, the President of France, the speech of the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Germany, I do not take Ukraine, Georgia, or the British, in any case, the choir was not absolutely accurate,” the politician said, noting that Russia “was no longer a kind of wall on which they train strikes with a tennis ball.”
The head of the relevant committee of the Federation Council does not exclude that this indicates some trend, which, in his opinion, “will highlight the current session [of the UN General Assembly], although this trend may be fully manifested in a year, in two or three.”
“I do not exclude that the current session in some sense can be a turning point,” – said Kosachev, explaining that “too many examples of how with the involvement of Russia manages to move forward in international affairs.”
As an example, he cited the situation in Syria, around Iran and North Korea.
“Unfortunately, this is not Ukraine, but I have no doubt that the Russian vision of the Ukrainian crisis will also be in demand over time,” the parliamentarian added.
This is due to the fact, he believes, that there is an “adequate, healthy perception of Russia as not just a possible – an integral participant in solving global problems of our time.”
“I don’t want to make a mistake, but I have a feeling that we are somewhere passing a point beyond which the movement will no longer be a backward movement, it will be a forward movement,” he added.
Another “interesting and important feeling” in this context, Kosachev called “a request for a Russian vision of how the modern world should develop.”
“I attended many meetings of the head of the Russian delegation [at the session of the General Assembly] of the Minister of Foreign Affairs Sergei Lavrov, I held my own meetings, and I was very pleased to see that if a year or two or five years ago the Russian opinion, the Russian vision of what is happening in the world, by and large, no one was interested, now the situation is different,” the chairman of the committee said.
In his opinion, this is due to the fact that "the so-called new liberal order, which is personified by the West, has no answers to the questions of how to solve world problems due to the obvious lack of ideas in the global space, the lack of ideas on how to solve the problems of the Middle East, the problems of terrorism, the problems of nuclear non-proliferation, the problems of migration."
"And here the demand for the Russian vision is becoming more and more obvious," Kosachev said, stressing that he considers "the current session a good one for the work of the Russian delegation, a good one for Russia."
