AdG became the second most popular in Germany
The anti-immigrant “Alternative for Germany” is breaking another record of popularity, and Angela Merkel’s ratings are falling.
Apparently, German residents are starting to get seriously tired of the immigration policy of Angela Merkel, thanks to which the country has become a coveted target for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
This is most evident in recent polls, according to which the anti-immigrant party Alternative for Germany is becoming increasingly popular, and the positions of the ruling bloc Merkel and Seehofer are weakening.
This week, the AfD broke another record, rising to the second place in the rating of people's sympathy.
The right-wing conservatives, with 17 percent of the popular vote, managed to beat the Social Democrats, who have about 16 percent.
The one-percentage-point gap can be attributed to a statistical error, but it is worth noting the fact that the AfD created in 2013 from a small group of Eurosceptic economists managed to turn into a serious political force.
The leadership in the general standings for the time being continues to hold the ruling bloc of the CSU/CDU, which has about 30 percent.
However, there is a tendency to the loss of points - back in April, support for Angela Merkel's bloc was four percentage points higher.
The personal rating of the German chancellor, who heads the German government for the fourth consecutive term, is also declining.
Today, 48 percent of Germans support Angela Merkel, which is 7 percent lower than last year.
The Social Democrats were followed by the Greens (15%), the Left (11%) and the Liberals (10%).
The Evolution of the “Alternative”
The Alternative for Germany party was founded in September 2012 on the basis of the Alternative Choice 2013 group, which included members of the Christian Democratic Union.
The group initially opposed the government’s course, but initially dealt only with economic issues, including the problems of the euro and cooperation within the EU.
At the same time, the group opposed Germany’s “sponsorship” of the EU’s weak economies, did not exclude the possibility of a return to the German mark and a full withdrawal of the country from the EU.
Against the background of the deepening immigration crisis, the political platform of the AfD has expanded.
In 2013, the group formed a full-fledged party, which occupied a niche of eurosceptics and began to harshly criticize the government for the failure of immigration policy.
In the last parliamentary elections in 2017, the AfD managed to break into the Bundestag for the first time, receiving 94 seats (out of 709).
Two representatives of the “Alternative for Germany” received seats in the European Parliament.
