Pushing and pushing - how right?
There is no word for pressure.
That's right, push.
The word "press" in the meaning of "pull, exert influence, influence" exists only phonetically, because we hear the sound [a] instead of [o] in the word "suffer".
We use this word, assuming that it comes from the word "pressure".
But "pressure" and "satisfy" are etymologically not only not close, but even in some sense opposite.
See for yourself.
To endure (church-book, obsolete) means "sufficiently, fully, sufficiently, to be sufficient for someone or something, to satisfy".
Satisfaction, pleasure - related words.
Previously, it still had the meaning of "not to depend on anything, to have a self-sufficient value" - "to satisfy oneself."
